<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Delile" authorityYear="1813" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Zygophyllaceae" genus="Balanites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Balanites aegyptiaca" order="Geraniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="aegyptiaca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Balanites aegyptiaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a small tree, native to much of Africa and parts of the Middle East. It naturally occurs in Morocco, relatively near to the Canary Islands. It is sometimes grown for its edible fruit or, less often, as a medicinal plant.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
In 2011, a single young individual of this species was found near to the port area in Los Cristianos in Tenerife (
<bibRefCitation author="Sanchez de Lorenzo Caceres, JM" journalOrPublisher="Bouteloua" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="82 - 84" refId="B6509557" refString="Sanchez de Lorenzo Caceres, JM, 2012. Sobre la presencia de Balanites aegyptiaca (L.) Del. (Zygophyllaceae) en Tenerife, Islas Canarias. Bouteloua 10: 82 - 84" title="Sobre la presencia de Balanites aegyptiaca (L.) Del. (Zygophyllaceae) en Tenerife, Islas Canarias" volume="10" year="2012">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sánchez">Sanchez</normalizedToken>
de Lorenzo 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Cáceres">Caceres</normalizedToken>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
). The species was most likely introduced by African immigrants. In the intervening years, the same individual was also repeatedly seen by us.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
In 2016, a further young individual of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Delile" authorityYear="1813" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Zygophyllaceae" genus="Balanites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Balanites aegyptiaca" order="Geraniales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="aegyptiaca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Balanites aegyptiaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was observed on rough ground in another village in the southern part of Tenerife, Guargacho. The introduction vector in this locality is unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
